1
00:00:06,168 --> 00:00:10,354
Thanks for coming, appreciate it.

2
00:00:10,354 --> 00:00:15,001
I'm going to tell you a little story.

3
00:00:15,001 --> 00:00:16,023
I think we're starting, right?

4
00:00:16,023 --> 00:00:17,325
Okay, good.

5
00:00:17,325 --> 00:00:19,468
A little while ago, I was...

6
00:00:20,784 --> 00:00:28,009
Googling myself up on the internets, and this thing kept popping up over and over again.

7
00:00:28,009 --> 00:00:32,053
Sid Meier says, games are a series of interesting decisions.

8
00:00:32,053 --> 00:00:39,639
And some people felt that was the most brilliant statement ever made in terms of games,

9
00:00:39,639 --> 00:00:43,482
and some people felt, Sid Meier, what an idiot.

10
00:00:43,482 --> 00:00:47,505
That's totally wrong. That's nothing.

11
00:00:48,138 --> 00:00:57,423
And I realized this was based on something I believe I said at a GDC presentation way back in

12
00:00:57,423 --> 00:01:03,346
the early, the misty days, early days of computer games. And I had never really thought too much

13
00:01:03,346 --> 00:01:09,149
about it, but it had kind of caught on with people writing books about games and trying to find

14
00:01:09,149 --> 00:01:10,070
fun and things like that.

15
00:01:11,152 --> 00:01:28,056
And I thought it might be interesting to kind of dig a little deeper into that idea and talk about interesting decisions and how I think it's a useful way of looking at games and maybe some ways that might be useful for other game designers.

16
00:01:28,056 --> 00:01:39,859
And I'm going to try not to talk about any specific genre of game or type of game, but talk more about decisions in general and how perhaps we can make them more interesting, how we can recognize them and things like that.

17
00:01:40,762 --> 00:01:47,423
Up until, up until today, really the only way that I've kind of talked about this idea

18
00:01:47,423 --> 00:01:51,305
is by breaking down the statement to series.

19
00:01:51,305 --> 00:01:55,226
And I think that, that speaks to the idea of pacing.

20
00:01:55,226 --> 00:01:57,006
The games have a pace to them.

21
00:01:57,006 --> 00:02:01,327
I think we all recognize, if we look at it, that certain games are very fast paced, certain

22
00:02:01,327 --> 00:02:02,768
games are slower paced.

23
00:02:02,768 --> 00:02:07,589
And that has an impact on the quality of the decisions and the nature of the decisions.

24
00:02:08,234 --> 00:02:11,496
And the other part is the idea of interesting decisions.

25
00:02:11,496 --> 00:02:14,157
And what makes a decision interesting?

26
00:02:14,157 --> 00:02:21,220
It's kind of almost easier to look at it at what is not an interesting decision.

27
00:02:21,220 --> 00:02:27,764
For example, if in a game you're presented with choice A, B, and C, and the player always

28
00:02:27,764 --> 00:02:32,086
chooses A, you probably haven't created an interesting decision for the player, and the

29
00:02:32,086 --> 00:02:34,347
computer should just choose A automatically and move on.

30
00:02:34,988 --> 00:02:40,132
Uh, again, if you present the player with a choice of A, B, and C, and the player kind

31
00:02:40,132 --> 00:02:44,654
of randomly just chooses one of those and moves on, again, you probably haven't provided

32
00:02:44,654 --> 00:02:46,335
the player with an interesting decision.

33
00:02:46,335 --> 00:02:52,879
So, uh, let's just kind of a very, uh, uh, first level look at that idea, but what we

34
00:02:52,879 --> 00:02:57,862
want to do today, I think, is dig a little deeper into the idea and try and, and, and

35
00:02:57,862 --> 00:03:03,866
talk about how we can make our decisions more interesting and, uh, make our games more fun.

36
00:03:06,672 --> 00:03:10,033
Now, I've gotten some pushback on this idea.

37
00:03:10,033 --> 00:03:13,655
People who disagree with the idea that games are a series of

38
00:03:13,655 --> 00:03:14,435
interesting decisions.

39
00:03:14,435 --> 00:03:17,636
And I'm really not going to argue about that today.

40
00:03:17,636 --> 00:03:21,017
I don't claim this is the only way of looking at games or

41
00:03:21,017 --> 00:03:22,998
applies to every single game.

42
00:03:22,998 --> 00:03:26,099
I think if you have a rhythm game like Guitar Hero.

43
00:03:27,352 --> 00:03:33,095
I could make a case that there are fascinating decisions in there, but it's more, it's not

44
00:03:33,095 --> 00:03:36,737
a game where interesting decisions are front and center.

45
00:03:36,737 --> 00:03:39,458
Also with a puzzle game, for example.

46
00:03:39,458 --> 00:03:43,821
So there may be some types of games for which the idea of interesting decisions is not a

47
00:03:43,821 --> 00:03:48,803
super useful way of looking at them, but I think for the majority of games it is useful

48
00:03:48,803 --> 00:03:53,466
to look at them in terms of the decisions that the player is presented with and how

49
00:03:53,466 --> 00:03:54,086
interesting they are.

50
00:03:55,670 --> 00:04:00,673
So how do we use this idea of interesting decisions?

51
00:04:00,673 --> 00:04:04,596
This is a picture of my son and I playing a computer game.

52
00:04:04,596 --> 00:04:09,499
To give you a sense of time, he's now a college graduate.

53
00:04:10,567 --> 00:04:15,769
So, this was a little while ago, but it kind of encapsulates for me what we're trying to

54
00:04:15,769 --> 00:04:16,449
do here.

55
00:04:16,449 --> 00:04:22,611
Why it is important that we make our games fun, that we find the fun, that we search

56
00:04:22,611 --> 00:04:27,472
for the fun and make them as fun to play as possible to kind of generate these moments

57
00:04:27,472 --> 00:04:28,772
for the player.

58
00:04:28,772 --> 00:04:33,493
And I think that thinking about interesting decisions is one way of finding the fun.

59
00:04:34,861 --> 00:04:37,061
So when is this idea useful?

60
00:04:37,061 --> 00:04:43,023
I think it's a useful concept during the design phase.

61
00:04:43,023 --> 00:04:45,943
One of the things that I see often

62
00:04:45,943 --> 00:04:49,604
is designs are kind of about putting together

63
00:04:49,604 --> 00:04:50,764
pieces of other games.

64
00:04:50,764 --> 00:04:53,265
What if we took a little bit of a shooter

65
00:04:53,265 --> 00:04:57,866
and added some StarCraft to it, and then we put in maybe

66
00:04:57,866 --> 00:05:00,006
some racing or whatever?

67
00:05:00,006 --> 00:05:00,746
Kind of.

68
00:05:02,164 --> 00:05:07,188
Lego game design, you know, the idea that, well, these other games are fun, so if I take

69
00:05:07,188 --> 00:05:11,171
pieces of these games, my game is itself going to be fun.

70
00:05:11,171 --> 00:05:17,337
Unfortunately, that doesn't often, that doesn't always work out, and I think it's a more useful

71
00:05:17,337 --> 00:05:21,440
way to look at a new game design in terms of what are the decisions that I'm presenting

72
00:05:21,440 --> 00:05:22,161
the player with.

73
00:05:22,161 --> 00:05:24,423
Are they, are they interesting?

74
00:05:24,423 --> 00:05:26,064
Put yourself in the player's point of view.

75
00:05:26,371 --> 00:05:32,075
in the player's chair and imagining what decisions can I create based on this scenario, this

76
00:05:32,075 --> 00:05:38,099
design, this world that I want to create. So I think it's a useful concept to apply

77
00:05:38,099 --> 00:05:42,463
even in the early design stages is to kind of imagine what are the actual decisions that

78
00:05:42,463 --> 00:05:48,127
the player is being asked to make during the course of the game. And I think this can help

79
00:05:48,127 --> 00:05:53,411
you to kind of crystallize what are the cool parts of this design idea that you have and

80
00:05:53,411 --> 00:05:54,692
what to kind of focus your early

81
00:05:55,243 --> 00:05:58,344
prototyping on, and I'm sure we all believe in, rapid

82
00:05:58,344 --> 00:06:00,464
prototyping. That's a whole other talk. Uh, the idea of

83
00:06:00,464 --> 00:06:07,966
focusing on interesting decisions, uh, can be useful

84
00:06:07,966 --> 00:06:10,747
during the development phase. As you're making a game, how

85
00:06:10,747 --> 00:06:13,407
do I make this game more fun? One of the key

86
00:06:13,407 --> 00:06:14,708
ways to do that is to look at the

87
00:06:14,708 --> 00:06:16,928
decisions that the player is making during the game and

88
00:06:16,928 --> 00:06:20,209
try to make them more interesting. Now, we'll talk

89
00:06:20,209 --> 00:06:22,110
more about what interesting means a little later, but,

90
00:06:22,110 --> 00:06:24,870
uh, again, during the development of the game.

91
00:06:25,688 --> 00:06:31,391
It's very useful to look at your decisions and see how the players respond to them and

92
00:06:31,391 --> 00:06:32,772
how interesting they are.

93
00:06:32,772 --> 00:06:37,715
It's also a useful concept as you're debugging the game.

94
00:06:37,715 --> 00:06:39,496
Where's the fun?

95
00:06:39,496 --> 00:06:43,018
I think we've all been near the end of the project.

96
00:06:43,018 --> 00:06:45,800
Every project of ours has what we call the valley of doom.

97
00:06:45,800 --> 00:06:51,183
About halfway to two-thirds of the way through, you're kind of convinced, why did we ever

98
00:06:51,183 --> 00:06:51,963
make this game?

99
00:06:51,963 --> 00:06:52,844
This is never going to work.

100
00:06:53,463 --> 00:06:55,785
This is not fun enough.

101
00:06:55,785 --> 00:06:59,288
I think focusing again on your decisions and trying to make

102
00:06:59,288 --> 00:07:02,310
them as interesting, as fun as possible, is something that's

103
00:07:02,310 --> 00:07:04,672
worth doing even during the later stages of the game.

104
00:07:04,672 --> 00:07:09,035
If you're trying to find and refine those last few ounces

105
00:07:09,035 --> 00:07:12,458
of fun, I think some of the ideas that we're going to talk

106
00:07:12,458 --> 00:07:15,641
about can be very useful for doing that.

107
00:07:15,641 --> 00:07:20,064
So what are some of the characteristics of

108
00:07:20,064 --> 00:07:21,165
interesting decisions?

109
00:07:23,408 --> 00:07:25,629
I think a very common one is they involve

110
00:07:25,629 --> 00:07:30,230
some sort of a tradeoff. That you can buy

111
00:07:30,230 --> 00:07:32,450
a big sword, but it costs you five hundred

112
00:07:32,450 --> 00:07:37,812
gold. I can use, I'm playing a racing game,

113
00:07:37,812 --> 00:07:40,692
I can choose this car, which is very fast,

114
00:07:40,692 --> 00:07:42,593
but doesn't have great handling, or I can choose

115
00:07:42,593 --> 00:07:45,133
this other car, has great handling, but it's not

116
00:07:45,133 --> 00:07:48,774
quite as, as fast. In a civilization game, I

117
00:07:48,774 --> 00:07:52,415
can build a defensive unit.

118
00:07:53,010 --> 00:07:57,832
and defend my city, but then I'm not generating more gold,

119
00:07:57,832 --> 00:08:00,933
or I can build a building that'll

120
00:08:00,933 --> 00:08:02,093
help my civilization advance.

121
00:08:02,093 --> 00:08:05,714
Or again, there's all these most interesting decisions,

122
00:08:05,714 --> 00:08:08,255
I'd almost say all of them, involve

123
00:08:08,255 --> 00:08:09,455
some sort of a trade-off.

124
00:08:09,455 --> 00:08:11,196
And it's just important to recognize

125
00:08:11,196 --> 00:08:14,077
what that trade-off is when you look at your decisions.

126
00:08:14,077 --> 00:08:20,378
And good decisions, I think, are situational.

127
00:08:20,378 --> 00:08:22,759
I think this is a very key idea that.

128
00:08:24,485 --> 00:08:33,252
When the decision is presented to the player, ideally it interacts in some very interesting way with the game situation.

129
00:08:33,252 --> 00:08:38,276
For example, we talked about the car, the fast car versus the car with good handling.

130
00:08:38,276 --> 00:08:43,179
Well, that is going to interact with what the next race is.

131
00:08:43,179 --> 00:08:44,360
What does that track look like?

132
00:08:44,360 --> 00:08:46,602
What are your particular skills as a driver?

133
00:08:46,602 --> 00:08:50,665
What are you trying to accomplish in this race?

134
00:08:50,665 --> 00:08:51,646
If you're playing a shooter.

135
00:08:52,173 --> 00:08:58,336
A trade-off might be between sneaking around and hiding behind cover or rushing forward.

136
00:08:58,336 --> 00:09:04,979
In Civ, I think there are many, many decisions that are really situational.

137
00:09:04,979 --> 00:09:10,421
I haven't explored much of the map yet, so I want a fast unit, I want a scout unit to run around and see what's out there.

138
00:09:11,199 --> 00:09:19,323
I'm just about to be attacked by Angus Khan and his horde of Mongols, so I need defensive units.

139
00:09:19,323 --> 00:09:22,845
I just discovered a new territory. I want to plant a city over there. I need to build some settlers.

140
00:09:22,845 --> 00:09:29,068
So it's one decision that the player is faced with. What do I build next?

141
00:09:29,068 --> 00:09:33,370
But it ties very directly into the game situation.

142
00:09:33,370 --> 00:09:36,512
And that's how you really add interest and variety to a lot of decisions,

143
00:09:36,512 --> 00:09:39,753
is by making them very situational, very dependent on.

144
00:09:40,282 --> 00:09:41,982
the current game situation.

145
00:09:41,982 --> 00:09:48,044
Some decisions can be personal.

146
00:09:48,044 --> 00:09:54,327
In other words, tied to your gaming style.

147
00:09:54,327 --> 00:09:56,508
Perhaps you are cautious.

148
00:09:57,197 --> 00:09:59,117
Turtle, enjoy the turtle strategy.

149
00:09:59,117 --> 00:10:02,718
And so you would build defensive units.

150
00:10:02,718 --> 00:10:08,139
You would build a very secure base from which you can then expand.

151
00:10:08,139 --> 00:10:09,060
Perhaps you're aggressive.

152
00:10:09,060 --> 00:10:10,980
You would build a whole different set of units.

153
00:10:10,980 --> 00:10:12,260
You'd have a whole different strategy.

154
00:10:12,260 --> 00:10:15,461
And again, the decision, this interesting decision,

155
00:10:15,461 --> 00:10:18,542
would allow you to express your personal play style.

156
00:10:20,812 --> 00:10:23,274
Decisions have persistence.

157
00:10:23,274 --> 00:10:25,376
They, interesting decisions, have persistence.

158
00:10:25,376 --> 00:10:28,739
They affect the game for a certain amount of time.

159
00:10:28,739 --> 00:10:30,241
Maybe it's a long period of time,

160
00:10:30,241 --> 00:10:31,162
maybe it's a short period of time.

161
00:10:31,162 --> 00:10:32,403
But you really want to be aware

162
00:10:32,403 --> 00:10:35,125
of what the persistence of a decision is.

163
00:10:35,125 --> 00:10:36,706
If it's a long-term decision.

164
00:10:37,899 --> 00:10:42,361
you really need to give the player enough information to feel comfortable making that decision.

165
00:10:42,361 --> 00:10:46,423
There's nothing worse than playing a game, doing something very early on,

166
00:10:46,423 --> 00:10:52,466
that you didn't quite understand, that totally messes up your play experience for the rest of the game.

167
00:10:52,466 --> 00:10:56,168
So it's important to understand what the persistence of your decisions are,

168
00:10:56,168 --> 00:10:57,969
and present them in a way appropriate to that.

169
00:10:57,969 --> 00:11:02,631
If a decision has a short persistence, it only affects the game for the next minute or two,

170
00:11:02,631 --> 00:11:04,652
you can be a little more...

171
00:11:06,428 --> 00:11:11,333
take more chances, maybe provide a lot of interesting options where the player realizes

172
00:11:11,333 --> 00:11:15,738
I'm just kind of going to try this out, it's not going to mess up my game forever, but

173
00:11:15,738 --> 00:11:17,719
I might try this new strategy or something different.

174
00:11:17,719 --> 00:11:26,628
So consider the persistence of the decisions when presenting them to the player.

175
00:11:26,628 --> 00:11:29,931
Here are some types of decisions.

176
00:11:30,850 --> 00:11:32,691
You might be looking at your game and saying,

177
00:11:32,691 --> 00:11:34,032
I need more decisions.

178
00:11:34,032 --> 00:11:35,554
I need to put some more stuff in there.

179
00:11:35,554 --> 00:11:37,676
It just doesn't feel like there's enough going on.

180
00:11:37,676 --> 00:11:39,797
I'm not giving the player enough stuff to do.

181
00:11:39,797 --> 00:11:42,540
So here's some of the types of decisions you might look at,

182
00:11:42,540 --> 00:11:46,884
see if there are opportunities to include these in your game.

183
00:11:46,884 --> 00:11:53,509
One of the classic decision types is risk versus reward.

184
00:11:54,363 --> 00:11:59,326
In a game like Civilization, it would be, do I defend my first city with a couple of

185
00:11:59,326 --> 00:12:07,010
phalanxes and then be kind of cautiously explore, or am I going to just kind of build a couple

186
00:12:07,010 --> 00:12:12,132
of scouts and just check everything out and hopefully the barbarians won't show up, but

187
00:12:12,132 --> 00:12:19,416
if they do, darn, might be choosing the fast car in a racing game.

188
00:12:19,416 --> 00:12:23,098
You know, I'm going to go as fast as I can and just hope I can make it around those curves,

189
00:12:23,098 --> 00:12:23,278
you know.

190
00:12:23,943 --> 00:12:29,527
So, often there are decisions that involve this idea of risk versus reward.

191
00:12:29,527 --> 00:12:33,330
I can take a greater risk with the potential of a greater reward,

192
00:12:33,330 --> 00:12:36,352
but if it doesn't work out, then the penalties are larger.

193
00:12:36,352 --> 00:12:39,374
So, this is one type of decision you might want to look at in your game.

194
00:12:39,374 --> 00:12:44,578
Is there an opportunity for finding some risk versus reward decisions?

195
00:12:44,578 --> 00:12:50,042
I think in almost any kind of game, you'll find these kind of opportunities for these decisions.

196
00:12:52,832 --> 00:13:00,118
Short-term versus long-term is another category of decision that you probably can find in

197
00:13:00,118 --> 00:13:01,058
your game design.

198
00:13:01,058 --> 00:13:06,363
In Civilization, again, building a wonder, which is something that's going to take a

199
00:13:06,363 --> 00:13:11,107
long time, but in the long-term it's going to do something wonderful for your Civilization.

200
00:13:11,107 --> 00:13:15,190
Versus building a chariot, which is going to be cool right away, it's going to be a

201
00:13:15,190 --> 00:13:19,874
lot of fun, but it might not have the same long-term impact on your game.

202
00:13:21,104 --> 00:13:25,865
in a racing game, perhaps buying that new car.

203
00:13:25,865 --> 00:13:30,626
It's going to take you a while to tune it up to maximum capacity,

204
00:13:30,626 --> 00:13:34,047
but in the long term it's going to be a good investment for your racing career.

205
00:13:34,047 --> 00:13:38,188
Short term decision might be to add some new tires or a bigger engine to your current car,

206
00:13:38,188 --> 00:13:43,010
which is going to help you in the short term, but a longer term,

207
00:13:43,010 --> 00:13:46,251
you still have to drive that same car.

208
00:13:47,226 --> 00:13:51,788
So look for opportunities to include short versus long term

209
00:13:51,788 --> 00:13:53,608
decisions in your game.

210
00:13:53,608 --> 00:14:00,271
Again, the idea of accommodating the player's play style.

211
00:14:00,271 --> 00:14:03,352
What we found in development is you really

212
00:14:03,352 --> 00:14:05,232
can't do enough of this.

213
00:14:05,232 --> 00:14:08,193
It's very tempting as a designer to imagine

214
00:14:08,193 --> 00:14:10,794
that everybody plays the game the same way that you do.

215
00:14:10,794 --> 00:14:13,475
And it's very tempting as a design and development group.

216
00:14:14,045 --> 00:14:17,488
to kind of feel that you represent all players.

217
00:14:17,488 --> 00:14:20,371
But there's an incredible range of players out there,

218
00:14:20,371 --> 00:14:22,733
and it's actually, it's increasing

219
00:14:22,733 --> 00:14:26,016
as games become more and more popular

220
00:14:26,016 --> 00:14:28,178
and more and more widespread.

221
00:14:28,178 --> 00:14:32,061
So try and include as many varieties of play style

222
00:14:32,061 --> 00:14:34,423
as you can in the decisions that you provide the players.

223
00:14:37,103 --> 00:14:41,664
We're now up to, I think, seven difficulty levels in Civilization

224
00:14:41,664 --> 00:14:44,685
to accommodate an incredibly wide range of players.

225
00:14:44,685 --> 00:14:51,326
The, again, defensive versus offensive, aggressive versus cautious,

226
00:14:51,326 --> 00:14:57,387
all these different play styles are things that you want to provide opportunities

227
00:14:57,387 --> 00:14:59,668
for the player to express as they play your game.

228
00:14:59,668 --> 00:15:06,869
Think about at what level your decisions are.

229
00:15:06,869 --> 00:15:06,889
I...

230
00:15:07,463 --> 00:15:12,546
I'm sorry that I keep coming back to Civilization, but it's a game that I'm somewhat familiar with.

231
00:15:12,546 --> 00:15:19,169
I think one of the strengths of Civilization is that it has things happening at various levels.

232
00:15:19,169 --> 00:15:22,031
There are things happening that are short-term.

233
00:15:22,031 --> 00:15:24,872
You're attacking a city that's close to you.

234
00:15:24,872 --> 00:15:27,393
You're defending this other city against the barbarians.

235
00:15:27,393 --> 00:15:30,855
You're exploring the coastline to see what's happening out there.

236
00:15:31,819 --> 00:15:33,820
You have some medium term things going on.

237
00:15:33,820 --> 00:15:38,641
You've decided that you're going to go for a military strategy.

238
00:15:38,641 --> 00:15:42,262
So your decisions are in the medium term,

239
00:15:42,262 --> 00:15:46,704
are geared to conquering, exploring,

240
00:15:46,704 --> 00:15:49,845
expanding your territory.

241
00:15:49,845 --> 00:15:54,086
Your long term strategy, your long term goal is to win the game.

242
00:15:54,086 --> 00:15:57,647
So your medium term strategy might not work out.

243
00:15:57,647 --> 00:16:00,868
You might need to change your strategy halfway through the game or whatever.

244
00:16:02,155 --> 00:16:06,877
Long term, you have the idea of winning the game.

245
00:16:06,877 --> 00:16:08,478
You might be going for a high score.

246
00:16:08,478 --> 00:16:14,282
You might be, have a goal that extends even outside

247
00:16:14,282 --> 00:16:16,623
of this particular game that you're playing.

248
00:16:16,623 --> 00:16:18,825
In a lot of game styles, types,

249
00:16:18,825 --> 00:16:21,026
you really need to include metagaming

250
00:16:21,026 --> 00:16:24,048
in your long term decision making.

251
00:16:24,048 --> 00:16:27,410
In other words, am I trying to get high ranking?

252
00:16:27,410 --> 00:16:29,351
Am I playing a multiplayer game where

253
00:16:30,098 --> 00:16:36,319
my clan is really counting on me or there are things that are happening even outside of one play game

254
00:16:36,319 --> 00:16:42,140
that are goals that the player has. And a game that has decisions at these various levels I think has

255
00:16:42,140 --> 00:16:51,762
it's kind of one of the keys to the one more turn quality of a game like Civilization or any game

256
00:16:51,762 --> 00:16:57,003
that is really draws a player in is going to have things happening at various levels so there's

257
00:16:57,003 --> 00:16:58,223
never a point where

258
00:16:58,668 --> 00:17:01,028
you're kind of all done with everything that you're trying to do.

259
00:17:01,028 --> 00:17:03,829
You might achieve one of your short-term goals,

260
00:17:03,829 --> 00:17:06,710
but you're in the middle of one of your medium-term goals,

261
00:17:06,710 --> 00:17:08,811
and your long-term goal is still out there,

262
00:17:08,811 --> 00:17:11,111
and as you develop a new short-term goal,

263
00:17:11,111 --> 00:17:12,632
maybe you achieve your medium-term goal,

264
00:17:12,632 --> 00:17:15,192
but there's always something that you're looking forward to,

265
00:17:15,192 --> 00:17:17,253
something that is coming up,

266
00:17:17,253 --> 00:17:19,994
that's important to you as a player.

267
00:17:19,994 --> 00:17:23,735
And the more you can get the player kind of thinking into the future,

268
00:17:23,735 --> 00:17:25,115
thinking about what am I going to do next.

269
00:17:26,044 --> 00:17:29,865
what are my plans, I think that's what's compelling,

270
00:17:29,865 --> 00:17:34,006
that's what creates the one more turn or the one more race

271
00:17:34,006 --> 00:17:36,627
or the one more battle or whatever,

272
00:17:36,627 --> 00:17:38,427
one more of whatever you have in your game,

273
00:17:38,427 --> 00:17:39,388
you want the player to kind

274
00:17:39,388 --> 00:17:41,868
of always be looking forward to that one more.

275
00:17:45,073 --> 00:17:51,519
Another type of decision that might not sound like it falls into the same category as some of these other ones,

276
00:17:51,519 --> 00:17:55,462
but is actually pretty important to the player, is the idea of customizing.

277
00:17:55,462 --> 00:18:02,188
Investing the player, if you're playing a racing game for example, is picking the color of your car.

278
00:18:02,188 --> 00:18:03,449
It seems fairly...

279
00:18:04,049 --> 00:18:07,091
straightforward, but that gives the player an investment in...

280
00:18:07,091 --> 00:18:11,993
they made a decision that invests them in the game. In Civilization, you can name

281
00:18:11,993 --> 00:18:12,473
your cities.

282
00:18:12,473 --> 00:18:17,255
It doesn't really affect the play of the game, but it's a decision that the player

283
00:18:17,255 --> 00:18:18,096
makes that

284
00:18:18,096 --> 00:18:20,016
that makes them more connected to this particular...

285
00:18:21,357 --> 00:18:24,919
game that they're playing. In a role-playing game, you might be able to choose the gender

286
00:18:24,919 --> 00:18:30,421
of your hero or different characteristics, dress them in different ways, whatever. Think

287
00:18:30,421 --> 00:18:36,204
about ways of investing the player in your game by inviting them to make decisions that

288
00:18:36,204 --> 00:18:40,907
let them express their personality or their gaming style.

289
00:18:40,907 --> 00:18:41,527
So those are

290
00:18:47,497 --> 00:18:51,478
some different types of decisions that I think it's worth looking at your game and trying

291
00:18:51,478 --> 00:18:57,979
to find ways to include in them. Now, when you present these decisions, it's really important

292
00:18:57,979 --> 00:19:03,281
how they're presented and how you respond to them. And we'll talk about that for just a second.

293
00:19:05,968 --> 00:19:09,450
information does the player have as they're about to make a decision?

294
00:19:09,450 --> 00:19:13,752
And it's very easy for us as designers who've played the game

295
00:19:13,752 --> 00:19:17,894
hundreds of times to assume the player knows everything that we know

296
00:19:17,894 --> 00:19:21,195
when we get to this point. And that's a very dangerous assumption.

297
00:19:21,195 --> 00:19:23,537
It's probably one of the most common...

298
00:19:24,393 --> 00:19:30,339
problems I see with games in development is that you assume the player knows this or that or whatever

299
00:19:30,339 --> 00:19:35,904
and you give the player this decision where they feel kind of totally lost and they're

300
00:19:35,904 --> 00:19:41,149
they make it and then they feel they're uncomfortable about making it and then they

301
00:19:41,149 --> 00:19:42,450
keep you know it's a kind of a

302
00:19:45,077 --> 00:19:45,977
gnaws at you.

303
00:19:45,977 --> 00:19:49,298
If you made a decision and you're not really sure whether

304
00:19:49,298 --> 00:19:53,819
it was the right one or what the impact of it is, it kind

305
00:19:53,819 --> 00:19:58,520
of really hurts your game playing experience.

306
00:19:58,520 --> 00:20:02,461
So I think it's worth almost erring on the side of

307
00:20:02,461 --> 00:20:05,002
presenting the player with too much information, or at

308
00:20:05,002 --> 00:20:08,103
least enough that they feel that they're comfortable with

309
00:20:08,103 --> 00:20:10,843
understanding what the choice is that you're

310
00:20:10,843 --> 00:20:12,424
giving the player.

311
00:20:14,797 --> 00:20:17,979
found that you want to manage the number of decisions.

312
00:20:17,979 --> 00:20:20,180
I think early on in some of our Civ designs,

313
00:20:20,180 --> 00:20:23,742
you were faced with choosing from among seven or nine

314
00:20:23,742 --> 00:20:26,084
or 12 different technologies you could research.

315
00:20:26,084 --> 00:20:30,306
And we really found that players have a tolerance

316
00:20:30,306 --> 00:20:34,068
for a smaller number of the, you know,

317
00:20:34,068 --> 00:20:37,170
I think three, five is a kind of a comfortable number

318
00:20:37,170 --> 00:20:41,112
to choose from, but just be aware that

319
00:20:41,680 --> 00:20:44,041
it's pretty easy to overwhelm players at this point.

320
00:20:44,041 --> 00:20:45,261
So, especially early in the game,

321
00:20:45,261 --> 00:20:48,262
you want them to feel that they're kind of going down.

322
00:20:48,262 --> 00:20:52,363
If they choose the default or they choose

323
00:20:52,363 --> 00:20:53,683
what the advisor is recommending,

324
00:20:53,683 --> 00:20:54,904
it's probably not such a bad decision.

325
00:20:54,904 --> 00:20:58,165
So, be sure there's enough information there

326
00:20:58,165 --> 00:21:02,586
when the decision is presented to the player.

327
00:21:02,586 --> 00:21:06,167
Another thing to be really aware of is that...

328
00:21:07,304 --> 00:21:10,106
there's a learning curve to playing your games that ties

329
00:21:10,106 --> 00:21:13,088
into how much information the player needs to be presented

330
00:21:13,088 --> 00:21:13,389
early on.

331
00:21:13,389 --> 00:21:18,333
And as the players get better, as you get better in your

332
00:21:18,333 --> 00:21:22,075
playing the game, your expectations for what you need

333
00:21:22,075 --> 00:21:24,377
to know to make an informed decision will change.

334
00:21:24,377 --> 00:21:31,162
So what we do almost from the beginning of our development

335
00:21:31,162 --> 00:21:33,784
is to try and introduce our game to new players and

336
00:21:33,784 --> 00:21:36,046
understand what the game feels like at the very early part of

337
00:21:36,046 --> 00:21:36,607
the process.

338
00:21:37,152 --> 00:21:41,633
of the learning curve.

339
00:21:41,633 --> 00:21:49,517
We have some friends in terms of kind of making players comfortable and enjoying our decisions,

340
00:21:49,517 --> 00:21:52,158
and we call them genre conventions.

341
00:21:52,158 --> 00:21:56,479
In other words, things that you know from having played other games in this genre.

342
00:21:56,479 --> 00:22:01,321
Very helpful in terms of interface conventions, for example, if you're playing a shooter,

343
00:22:01,321 --> 00:22:05,823
you can understand which button does what, and when you move the joystick this way, this

344
00:22:05,823 --> 00:22:06,863
is what's supposed to happen.

345
00:22:08,330 --> 00:22:12,072
By, for goodness sake, use those genre conventions.

346
00:22:12,072 --> 00:22:15,674
There's nothing more disconcerting than having the wrong thing happen

347
00:22:15,674 --> 00:22:18,675
when you press a button that in every other game does X.

348
00:22:18,675 --> 00:22:25,378
But just satisfying the genre conventions is not really enough to make a new game.

349
00:22:25,378 --> 00:22:31,181
So that's why I suggest you take advantage of all those conventions out there

350
00:22:31,181 --> 00:22:32,922
to make the game very comfortable to your player.

351
00:22:33,569 --> 00:22:40,551
but then do more, add something new, a new button that does something cool, a new feature.

352
00:22:40,551 --> 00:22:45,573
But be sure and take advantage of these conventions because they will make the player feel very,

353
00:22:45,573 --> 00:22:51,075
very comfortable in your world and again start thinking in the future about what they want

354
00:22:51,075 --> 00:22:56,197
to do as opposed to thinking about the present and how does this game actually work.

355
00:22:58,510 --> 00:23:02,471
It's one of the reasons that a lot of our games involve historical topics,

356
00:23:02,471 --> 00:23:08,992
is because the player can bring to a historical topic a lot of information that they kind of already know.

357
00:23:08,992 --> 00:23:13,253
And it's important to reinforce that information for the player.

358
00:23:13,253 --> 00:23:19,794
If they run into Genghis Khan in a Civilization game, he's going to be kind of angry and aggressive.

359
00:23:19,794 --> 00:23:24,595
I think that makes the player feel, I kind of get where he's coming from.

360
00:23:24,595 --> 00:23:28,015
You don't have to explain it in a massive civilopedia.

361
00:23:28,648 --> 00:23:31,910
or Gandhi, you know, he's got his own personality.

362
00:23:31,910 --> 00:23:35,572
So, uh, or if you're building a game about, uh,

363
00:23:35,572 --> 00:23:39,674
railroads or pirates, there's, there's a lot that the player

364
00:23:39,674 --> 00:23:44,157
can bring to a topic like that to, uh, that they already know.

365
00:23:44,157 --> 00:23:46,699
And all you need to do really, uh, design-wise,

366
00:23:46,699 --> 00:23:48,340
is to kind of reinforce a little bit of that.

367
00:23:48,340 --> 00:23:51,722
And, you know, if there's an evil Spaniard in a...

368
00:23:53,147 --> 00:23:57,450
beautiful governor's daughter and a few things like that, you understand that this is the

369
00:23:57,450 --> 00:24:02,933
world that's being created for you and you can kind of go forward.

370
00:24:02,933 --> 00:24:08,096
It's not only true of historical games, but we have a world where sci-fi games have their

371
00:24:08,096 --> 00:24:08,917
own set of conventions.

372
00:24:08,917 --> 00:24:14,941
And it's important that you understand them and make the player feel comfortable in that

373
00:24:14,941 --> 00:24:15,621
world.

374
00:24:15,621 --> 00:24:20,764
Now if you want to break a few or change it up a little bit, that's fine, but make sure

375
00:24:20,764 --> 00:24:22,225
the player understands where.

376
00:24:22,675 --> 00:24:26,559
that you're doing that and and that this is the cool part of your game

377
00:24:26,559 --> 00:24:30,642
but this doesn't destroy, you know, make all the other decisions in the game

378
00:24:30,642 --> 00:24:33,685
ones where they don't, they kind of have to figure out on their own what the

379
00:24:33,685 --> 00:24:37,649
what the world is like. It's one of the reasons I love zombies

380
00:24:37,649 --> 00:24:44,195
is, um, they're very clear. Zombies, the motivation of zombies is clear

381
00:24:44,195 --> 00:24:48,438
very little explanation has to happen to the player. You know, zombies have

382
00:24:49,447 --> 00:24:53,468
have their problems and it's very clear how you need to solve those problems.

383
00:24:53,468 --> 00:25:01,612
So, it's kind of an example of a decision that doesn't have to, you don't have to add

384
00:25:01,612 --> 00:25:06,074
a lot of information to the player. They pretty much know what to do.

385
00:25:06,074 --> 00:25:11,476
And so it's a very clear, setting up a decision like that is very clear.

386
00:25:13,304 --> 00:25:17,049
On the other hand, once a player has made a decision, it is very, very important how

387
00:25:17,049 --> 00:25:19,513
you respond to this decision.

388
00:25:19,513 --> 00:25:23,158
And it's another place where a lot of times we kind of fall down.

389
00:25:23,158 --> 00:25:28,346
The worst thing you can do is basically just move on.

390
00:25:28,985 --> 00:25:43,318
Uh, there's nothing more paranoia inducing than having made a decision and, and, and the game just kind of goes on and you, you know, at least give a sound effect or something to indicate that, yes, I heard what you said and I'm, I'm, I'm going to do it, you know.

391
00:25:43,318 --> 00:25:48,943
Uh, ideally, uh, the more you can respond, uh, the better.

392
00:25:48,943 --> 00:25:50,485
We found in, in, uh, in, in.

393
00:25:52,144 --> 00:25:56,107
revolution that players were just so happy

394
00:25:56,107 --> 00:26:00,591
to get this feedback from. A lot of times you'd be talking to a leader of another

395
00:26:00,591 --> 00:26:04,734
civilization and you'd be negotiating about war, peace, or trading things.

396
00:26:04,734 --> 00:26:08,997
But they would make these kind of aside comments like, you know,

397
00:26:08,997 --> 00:26:11,760
I noticed you moved your phalanx next to my city over there.

398
00:26:11,760 --> 00:26:12,280
What's up with that?

399
00:26:14,307 --> 00:26:17,430
Um, that unit you have has won five battles, you know, in a row.

400
00:26:17,430 --> 00:26:19,431
That's very cool.

401
00:26:19,431 --> 00:26:24,555
Or they really started to interact with you as a player and give you almost more feedback

402
00:26:24,555 --> 00:26:26,016
than, than, than necessary.

403
00:26:26,016 --> 00:26:31,621
But it's very important that you respond to the player as they make a decision in a, in

404
00:26:31,621 --> 00:26:37,825
a way that, uh, one, they understand that you heard them and, and, and you're moving

405
00:26:37,825 --> 00:26:38,566
on.

406
00:26:38,566 --> 00:26:42,369
But you can actually build on that to suggest, uh, different things.

407
00:26:42,795 --> 00:26:48,902
Like, okay, you know, you chose that option, that could work, but, you know, if you'd done

408
00:26:48,902 --> 00:26:50,845
this, maybe this might have happened.

409
00:26:52,159 --> 00:27:00,585
fine, you know, attack me, you know, but you could have, we could have been friends and I would have given you some technology or whatever.

410
00:27:00,585 --> 00:27:04,387
So, you can introduce into your response to the player

411
00:27:04,387 --> 00:27:10,512
some ideas about other courses of action that they could take or what they might do the next time they play the game.

412
00:27:10,512 --> 00:27:14,134
So, responding to the player's decision is a time to really...

413
00:27:15,837 --> 00:27:20,360
think about how you do that and make it a kind of a rewarding experience.

414
00:27:20,360 --> 00:27:26,223
It kind of comes down to the, does anybody know I'm here factor.

415
00:27:26,223 --> 00:27:30,005
Basically, if you're playing a single player game,

416
00:27:31,005 --> 00:27:37,709
You are imagining yourself as the leader of a great civilization, or a super-duper race car driver,

417
00:27:37,709 --> 00:27:44,733
or science fiction fantasy hero with huge bulging muscles.

418
00:27:44,733 --> 00:27:48,395
And, but you're really just sitting there in front of your computer in your lonely room

419
00:27:48,395 --> 00:27:53,938
with the glow from the monitor on your face.

420
00:27:53,938 --> 00:27:58,340
And it's really important to let the player know that you know that they're there,

421
00:27:58,340 --> 00:27:59,841
that you know that they're playing.

422
00:28:00,151 --> 00:28:06,915
that you're a partner with them, you're right there next to them all the way and yes, you

423
00:28:06,915 --> 00:28:11,719
are the leader of a great civilization or yes, you are a fantastic race car driver or

424
00:28:11,719 --> 00:28:18,824
yes, your muscles are super bulging. And the response that you give to the player's decisions

425
00:28:18,824 --> 00:28:26,609
is really the tool that you have to do that. Whether it's a sound, a text, visual, a graphic,

426
00:28:26,609 --> 00:28:29,731
you know, think of the tools that you have to kind of...

427
00:28:30,150 --> 00:28:35,115
really reinforce what the player, the fantasy that the player is creating in their mind

428
00:28:35,115 --> 00:28:42,962
and really allow them to, to enjoy that.

429
00:28:42,962 --> 00:28:49,648
So what I'm, what I hope is part of your design process is what, what I'm calling a decision

430
00:28:49,648 --> 00:28:55,033
feedback loop. In other words, that you're constantly iterating on your design and

431
00:28:56,603 --> 00:29:03,187
uh, those ideas that you get from your players, etc. are being tried out and I mean, it's

432
00:29:03,187 --> 00:29:08,491
really, uh, can't recommend enough the idea of having a tight iteration loop on your game

433
00:29:08,491 --> 00:29:13,635
design and having as many people play it as possible and try and feed that, uh, feed that

434
00:29:13,635 --> 00:29:14,936
information back into your design.

435
00:29:14,936 --> 00:29:16,457
The more times you can go around that loop.

436
00:29:17,353 --> 00:29:19,574
I think the better your game is going to be.

437
00:29:19,574 --> 00:29:21,896
So it's really, I think, important to try and structure

438
00:29:21,896 --> 00:29:25,219
your technology or design process

439
00:29:25,219 --> 00:29:27,401
to allow that kind of iteration.

440
00:29:27,401 --> 00:29:29,583
So hopefully you're listening to a lot of players

441
00:29:29,583 --> 00:29:31,384
and getting a lot of feedback.

442
00:29:31,384 --> 00:29:33,146
Obviously, you can't do everything.

443
00:29:33,146 --> 00:29:34,947
Some ideas might be good or bad.

444
00:29:34,947 --> 00:29:38,250
But the more ideas that you are able to kind of process,

445
00:29:38,250 --> 00:29:40,352
I think the better your game will be.

446
00:29:41,785 --> 00:29:49,771
It is useful to kind of understand the different kinds of players that you will be dealing

447
00:29:49,771 --> 00:29:53,795
with and talking to as you kind of expose your game to your playtesters and your friends

448
00:29:53,795 --> 00:29:54,575
and your co-

449
00:29:55,112 --> 00:29:58,974
coworkers or whoever you are able to get to test your game,

450
00:29:58,974 --> 00:30:01,456
you're going to get a lot of different kinds of response.

451
00:30:01,456 --> 00:30:06,359
And it's really up to you as a designer to filter that and

452
00:30:06,359 --> 00:30:09,541
decide what is really going to help my game, what is going to

453
00:30:09,541 --> 00:30:12,663
make it better, or what's an interesting idea but doesn't

454
00:30:12,663 --> 00:30:15,625
fit this game or is not going to work.

455
00:30:15,625 --> 00:30:20,528
So it's kind of useful to know a little bit about the types

456
00:30:20,528 --> 00:30:23,190
of players that you'll probably start to get some feedback

457
00:30:23,190 --> 00:30:23,410
from.

458
00:30:24,989 --> 00:30:31,572
Um, the first player is Mr. Kickbutt here. And you may, I'm not going to ask you to raise

459
00:30:31,572 --> 00:30:39,416
your hand, but some of you may recognize yourself in this, in this player. Um, this is the player

460
00:30:39,416 --> 00:30:45,219
who only cares about winning the game. They're only, if they won the game, it's great, it's

461
00:30:45,219 --> 00:30:46,460
awesome, it's the best game ever.

