00:37:01,798 --> 00:37:03,499
design their game and not the game that you're making.

540
00:37:03,499 --> 00:37:05,460
OK, so we've got a game that we're working on.

541
00:37:05,460 --> 00:37:05,600
And.

542
00:37:14,106 --> 00:37:18,491
It's cool, it's pretty good, it's fun, kind of fun, but how do we make it better?

543
00:37:18,491 --> 00:37:22,936
How do we take the decisions that we have and make them even more interesting?

544
00:37:25,430 --> 00:37:30,393
The first thing that we look at, I think, is often just the balance of the decisions.

545
00:37:30,393 --> 00:37:35,676
A lot of times, just simply fixing the balance is going to help your decisions to be, make

546
00:37:35,676 --> 00:37:36,796
your decisions a lot more interesting.

547
00:37:36,796 --> 00:37:41,259
We talked at the very beginning about how most decisions involve some sort of trade-off.

548
00:37:41,259 --> 00:37:44,080
You know, I'm going to buy a sword, but it's going to cost me 300 gold.

549
00:37:44,080 --> 00:37:47,702
You may find that nobody's buying that sword.

550
00:37:47,702 --> 00:37:50,204
Well, that might be an indication that it should cost 200 gold.

551
00:37:51,407 --> 00:37:56,951
Or you may find that everybody is walking around with one of these $300 swords.

552
00:37:56,951 --> 00:37:58,472
Maybe it's, maybe it should be $500.

553
00:37:58,472 --> 00:38:03,976
So, one of the early things to look at is just, is it simply a balance issue.

554
00:38:03,976 --> 00:38:08,960
That my decision would be more interesting with a different sort of balance attached to it.

555
00:38:08,960 --> 00:38:12,863
Again, it can apply to any, if you have a racing game, you know,

556
00:38:12,863 --> 00:38:17,987
those cool tires are too expensive or too cheap, et cetera.

557
00:38:20,083 --> 00:38:22,523
Another way of making your decisions more interesting,

558
00:38:22,523 --> 00:38:24,684
I think, is to make them more important.

559
00:38:24,684 --> 00:38:28,005
Again, we're kind of talking in a very kind of abstract terms,

560
00:38:28,005 --> 00:38:29,725
but your game is about something.

561
00:38:29,725 --> 00:38:30,805
It's about something cool.

562
00:38:30,805 --> 00:38:31,585
It's about something neat.

563
00:38:31,585 --> 00:38:38,007
Make the decision, tie more directly and coolly

564
00:38:38,007 --> 00:38:41,287
into what your game is about.

565
00:38:41,287 --> 00:38:42,548
Make it more significant.

566
00:38:42,548 --> 00:38:48,269
Make the sword shiny and have a sharpie edge made out

567
00:38:48,269 --> 00:38:49,109
of titanium or something.

568
00:38:49,949 --> 00:38:57,673
You know, find ways to bring your game fantasy back into decisions to make them feel more important.

569
00:38:57,673 --> 00:39:04,377
Again, in Civilization, talking to the other leaders gives the decisions that you make there

570
00:39:04,377 --> 00:39:06,358
and the interaction that you have feel more important.

571
00:39:06,358 --> 00:39:09,019
I mean, those could be simple check boxes, you know,

572
00:39:09,019 --> 00:39:11,921
but having the other leader there animated and talking to you

573
00:39:11,921 --> 00:39:16,043
gives those kind of decisions a feeling of greater importance.

574
00:39:16,043 --> 00:39:17,203
Whatever your game is about.

575
00:39:17,859 --> 00:39:20,681
Feed more of that directly into your decision making.

576
00:39:20,681 --> 00:39:24,843
And I think it'll feel more important and have more

577
00:39:24,843 --> 00:39:25,303
character.

578
00:39:25,303 --> 00:39:31,646
Control the amount of information that the player has

579
00:39:31,646 --> 00:39:34,188
when they're making decisions.

580
00:39:34,188 --> 00:39:37,930
Again, coming back to civilization, we have a system

581
00:39:37,930 --> 00:39:40,831
where the world is gradually revealed.

582
00:39:40,831 --> 00:39:44,573
And that really affects a lot of the decisions that the

583
00:39:44,573 --> 00:39:45,834
player makes.

584
00:39:47,036 --> 00:39:50,799
Imagine a Civ game where the entire map was revealed at the very beginning.

585
00:39:50,799 --> 00:39:54,522
I mean, that would be a very different game experience.

586
00:39:54,522 --> 00:39:59,866
And so by managing the amount of information that the player has, you can make your decisions

587
00:39:59,866 --> 00:40:00,986
more interesting.

588
00:40:00,986 --> 00:40:05,650
In other situations, giving the player more information might be the way of making that

589
00:40:05,650 --> 00:40:07,952
decision more interesting.

590
00:40:07,952 --> 00:40:12,475
If they knew more about what was going on in the rest of the world, they might feel

591
00:40:12,475 --> 00:40:15,317
better and find the decisions to be more interesting.

592
00:40:15,317 --> 00:40:15,397
So...

593
00:40:15,917 --> 00:40:20,299
look at the amount of information that the player has as they

594
00:40:20,299 --> 00:40:23,301
look at the decisions and see if

595
00:40:23,301 --> 00:40:27,103
either giving them more information or less information would be a way to make

596
00:40:27,103 --> 00:40:29,284
that particular decision more more interesting.

597
00:40:33,025 --> 00:40:35,608
the number of choices you give the player.

598
00:40:35,608 --> 00:40:40,654
As designers, we think we get paid by the decision, by the choice.

599
00:40:40,654 --> 00:40:44,958
The more choices we give the player, the better designers we are,

600
00:40:44,958 --> 00:40:46,000
and the more we ought to get paid.

601
00:40:47,691 --> 00:40:55,494
Be careful of that philosophy because the player is easily overwhelmed and you may find

602
00:40:55,494 --> 00:41:00,697
that by managing the number of choices that you give the player, you actually make the

603
00:41:00,697 --> 00:41:05,479
decision more interesting, often by kind of cutting them down, maybe combining two or

604
00:41:05,479 --> 00:41:06,879
three together, things like that.

605
00:41:06,879 --> 00:41:12,302
Look at the number of decisions that you're providing the player to see if it might not

606
00:41:12,302 --> 00:41:14,603
be more interesting if you did it a little differently.

607
00:41:16,350 --> 00:41:23,834
Um, making them more flavorful. Uh, this is really a presentation issue. You know, a lot of

608
00:41:23,834 --> 00:41:29,517
times designers, we think we can, we can design a game text only with programmer graphics and it

609
00:41:29,517 --> 00:41:30,418
would be totally cool.

610
00:41:31,308 --> 00:41:32,588
Well, that's fine.

611
00:41:32,588 --> 00:41:35,529
But take advantage of those artists, those writers, those

612
00:41:35,529 --> 00:41:39,270
sound guys, all those other people that are working on

613
00:41:39,270 --> 00:41:43,612
your project to add more flavor and interest and

614
00:41:43,612 --> 00:41:46,373
excitement to your decisions.

615
00:41:46,373 --> 00:41:49,994
Again, coming back to civilization, interacting

616
00:41:49,994 --> 00:41:52,655
directly with the great leaders.

617
00:41:52,655 --> 00:41:55,575
In a racing game, as you add stuff to your car, it rotates

618
00:41:55,575 --> 00:41:56,896
around and light shines on it.

619
00:41:57,462 --> 00:42:00,285
and cool stuff happens with your hero.

620
00:42:00,285 --> 00:42:06,090
You see the new equipment being put on them,

621
00:42:06,090 --> 00:42:08,232
and they smile, and you find ways

622
00:42:08,232 --> 00:42:12,016
to just add that kind of game flavor to your decisions,

623
00:42:12,016 --> 00:42:13,478
and that's another way of making them more interesting.

624
00:42:13,478 --> 00:42:17,782
Look at how much time you're giving the player

625
00:42:17,782 --> 00:42:18,783
to make a decision.

626
00:42:18,783 --> 00:42:21,225
It's...I think it's...

627
00:42:22,709 --> 00:42:27,472
It's really key to understand that most genres are almost

628
00:42:27,472 --> 00:42:30,214
defined by the amount of time you give the player.

629
00:42:30,214 --> 00:42:34,037
It may seem like a minor issue, but if you change the

630
00:42:34,037 --> 00:42:36,418
amount of time that you give the player to make decisions,

631
00:42:36,418 --> 00:42:38,660
you're almost stepping into a new genre.

632
00:42:38,660 --> 00:42:43,023
If you're playing Civilization, which is turn

633
00:42:43,023 --> 00:42:44,604
based, you make it real time.

634
00:42:44,604 --> 00:42:47,446
All of a sudden, you're playing a game like Age of

635
00:42:47,446 --> 00:42:48,166
Empires or RTS.

636
00:42:49,907 --> 00:42:54,630
playing a shooter and it's moving very quickly and you slow down the time frame, all of a sudden

637
00:42:54,630 --> 00:43:01,833
you're playing a sneaking around game and a whole different feeling. So by looking at the amount of

638
00:43:01,833 --> 00:43:05,995
time you're giving the player to make decisions, you're almost defining what genre you're in.

639
00:43:05,995 --> 00:43:12,199
And do you want to slide your game a little more in one direction, genre direction or another?

640
00:43:12,199 --> 00:43:18,242
And there's also basically an inverse relationship between how long you give the player to make a

641
00:43:18,242 --> 00:43:19,042
decision and how...

642
00:43:19,400 --> 00:43:21,601
deep and complex that decision is going to be.

643
00:43:21,601 --> 00:43:24,742
You have to be careful to manage that balance.

644
00:43:24,742 --> 00:43:28,303
If you're playing a game with very complicated decisions that

645
00:43:28,303 --> 00:43:31,424
come at you one after the other, the player's basically

646
00:43:31,424 --> 00:43:36,466
going to feel overwhelmed and out of control,

647
00:43:36,466 --> 00:43:38,547
never having a chance to look forward and anticipate

648
00:43:38,547 --> 00:43:40,408
what they're going to do next, but always trying to figure out

649
00:43:40,408 --> 00:43:41,788
what's going on right now.

650
00:43:41,788 --> 00:43:44,429
On the other hand, if you give the player

651
00:43:44,429 --> 00:43:47,510
some very simple decisions at a very slow pace,

652
00:43:49,370 --> 00:43:54,072
they're kind of bored. That's a boring game. I won't mention any names, but.

653
00:43:54,072 --> 00:44:03,596
And the last way to make a decision more interesting is to get rid of it. If you've tried all these

654
00:44:03,596 --> 00:44:10,180
things and they don't work, maybe the decision just is not one that should, you know, should

655
00:44:10,180 --> 00:44:16,322
take out of your game. Be, be ruthless in terms of cutting things out. Generally, we

656
00:44:16,322 --> 00:44:17,123
find that.

657
00:44:17,734 --> 00:44:20,797
probably a third of the things that we try, if not more,

658
00:44:20,797 --> 00:44:26,423
eventually end up getting taken out of the game because they just aren't fun and interesting enough.

659
00:44:26,423 --> 00:44:30,427
So again, as designers we don't get paid by the decision,

660
00:44:30,427 --> 00:44:32,889
we get paid by how good our game's at the end of the day,

661
00:44:32,889 --> 00:44:37,454
and it may be the best decision to get rid of your...

662
00:44:37,454 --> 00:44:38,335
whatever's not working.

663
00:44:39,987 --> 00:44:43,029
So we've talked about, in theoretical terms,

664
00:44:43,029 --> 00:44:45,911
all these different ways of looking at your decisions,

665
00:44:45,911 --> 00:44:49,274
perhaps making them more interesting,

666
00:44:49,274 --> 00:44:53,757
finding ways to maximize the decision-making process

667
00:44:53,757 --> 00:44:55,258
of your game.

668
00:44:55,258 --> 00:44:57,659
But really, I don't want to.

669
00:44:58,973 --> 00:45:02,454
I don't want to forget that your game is more than just decisions.

670
00:45:02,454 --> 00:45:07,576
I think once you've got the game working and you've got all these cool decisions in there

671
00:45:07,576 --> 00:45:13,117
and the players are, you've really kind of tuned that part of the game, you need to,

672
00:45:13,117 --> 00:45:14,998
to remystify your game.

673
00:45:14,998 --> 00:45:19,479
Really make it about the fantasy that you're trying to create for the player.

674
00:45:19,479 --> 00:45:25,820
It's, it's the combination of this wonderful fantasy world that you create and the interesting

675
00:45:25,820 --> 00:45:28,261
decisions that the player gets to make in that, in that world.

676
00:45:28,681 --> 00:45:32,305
that really is the sum total of the quality of your game.

677
00:45:32,305 --> 00:45:37,470
So we want you to maximize the awesomeness of your game world,

678
00:45:37,470 --> 00:45:39,993
of the graphics, of the way that you present it.

679
00:45:39,993 --> 00:45:46,700
These are all very important tools that augment these decisions that you have

680
00:45:46,700 --> 00:45:51,805
to make the game maximally awesome.

681
00:45:54,582 --> 00:45:57,624
And we encourage you to make it epic.

682
00:45:57,624 --> 00:46:03,286
Again, we're inviting the player to step into your

683
00:46:03,286 --> 00:46:06,728
designed world and become some awesome character.

684
00:46:06,728 --> 00:46:12,950
And we're fulfilling this fantasy for us to step out of

685
00:46:12,950 --> 00:46:18,033
our humdrum lives and become great heroes.

686
00:46:19,381 --> 00:46:23,204
I don't want to, by focusing on all the kind of minutiae of making decisions and how to

687
00:46:23,204 --> 00:46:27,908
make them better, lose sight of the story that you're telling.

688
00:46:28,282 --> 00:46:32,804
the world that you're inviting the player to step into, and

689
00:46:32,804 --> 00:46:38,027
the ways that you can really tie your decisions to

